Here's the proper approach using MAUI's lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In your `App.xaml.cs`**, hook into the `Window` lifecycle:

```csharp
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
{
    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

    window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
    {
        if (Application.Current?.MainPage is NavigationPage nav
            && nav.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
        {
            page.SaveDraft();
        }
    };

    window.Activated += (s, e) =>
    {
        if (Application.Current?.MainPage is NavigationPage nav
            && nav.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
        {
            page.RestoreDraft();
        }
    };

    return window;
}
```

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`**:

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        var draft = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
        if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(draft))
            NoteEditor.Text = draft;
    }

    // Clear draft when the user explicitly saves
    private void OnSaveClicked(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // ... your save logic ...
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires when the app goes to background — save here.
- **`Window.Activated`** fires on resume — restore here.
- **`Preferences`** is lightweight key-value storage, ideal for small text. For large drafts, use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with file I/O instead.
- Clear the draft after an explicit save to avoid stale data.
